\subsection{Any standard R distribution}{

For any distribution with an \verb{r<name>()} function in the search path, pass
the suffix as the string.  All \code{coord_args} entries are forwarded as named
arguments.  No data-informed scale defaults are applied — choose parameters
appropriate for your map's antigenic unit scale.

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{# Student-t (heavier tails than normal)
optimizeMapStart(map, 2, 100, starting_coords = "t",
                 coord_args = list(df = 5))

# Cauchy (very heavy tails)
optimizeMapStart(map, 2, 100, starting_coords = "cauchy",
                 coord_args = list(location = 0, scale = 3))

# Exponential (one-sided; may be useful with centring)
optimizeMapStart(map, 2, 100, starting_coords = "exp",
                 coord_args = list(rate = 0.2))
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Using custom functions}{

The function interface is designed to match the five starting-coordinate
algorithms in a companion analysis script.  Any function that accepts
\verb{(n_ag, n_sr, ndim, D)} and returns a named list with \code{ag_coords} and
\code{sr_coords} can be supplied directly:

\if{html}{\out{<div class="sourceCode r">}}\preformatted{optimizeMapStart(
  map, 2, 100,
  starting_coords = start_lhs   # Latin Hypercube
)

optimizeMapStart(
  map, 2, 100,
  starting_coords = start_cmds_perturbed,
  coord_args = list(noise_sd = 1.5)
)
}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Dimensional annealing}{

\code{starting_coords} is incompatible with \code{options = list(dim_annealing = TRUE)}
because dimensional annealing starts in 5D and requires random
initialisation in that higher space.  A warning is issued and dimensional
annealing is disabled when both are supplied.
}
